******
[3]
Date: Thu, 16 Feb 2006
From: Alan Shlosberg <alans@moag.gov.il>

We are trying to learn more of the epidemiology of the present
outbreak of aflatoxin toxicosis in dogs in Israel (about 25 dead
animals so far) induced by dog food produced by the Diamond company
in the USA. What we would be interested to learn is:
1. Whereas the FDA reported that "some of the recalled product was
exported to at least 29 countries, including countries in the EU", it
seems strange that there were cases of aflatoxicosis in dogs recorded
only in Israel (as far as we know). Does anyone know of other cases
occurring outside the USA?
2. Which countries have imported dog food from Diamond in the last 3 months?
3. Which of these countries routinely examine imported dog food for mycotoxins?
4. Have there been analyses for aflatoxin or other mycotoxins in
these countries in suspect Diamond feeds since the USA recall?
5. Have there been recalls of suspect Diamond feed in these countries?
--
Alan Shlosberg
Veterinary Toxicologist
Israeli Veterinary Services and Animal Health
e-mail <alans@moag.gov.il>
[According to today's (16 Feb 2006) information from the Teaching
Veterinary Hospital, 42 dogs have been hospitalised there so far, all
showing typical clinical and clinico-pathological signs of aflatoxin
poisoning. 23 of them have died, 6 recovered and released, 13 remain
hospitalised.
The number of pet dogs in Israel is estimated to exceed 200 000.
According to official state regulations, dog owners are required to
identify their dogs by approved electronic chips. At present, more
than 144 000 electronically identifiable dogs are included in the
Central Dog Registry, maintained by the State Veterinary Services.
- Mod.AS]
[Diamond is unaware of any recall food making its way into
distribution channels, except in Israel. - Mod.TG]
